WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:10.850 align:middle line:90%


00:00:10.850 --> 00:00:13.340 align:middle line:84%
>> I'm radio and television
host, Jimmy Church.

00:00:13.340 --> 00:00:16.100 align:middle line:84%
And I'm here to uncover
the truth about some

00:00:16.100 --> 00:00:18.170 align:middle line:90%
of life's biggest mysteries.

00:00:18.170 --> 00:00:21.830 align:middle line:84%
If this is revealed,
everything has to be rewritten.

00:00:21.830 --> 00:00:25.940 align:middle line:84%
My guest today is Avi Loeb,
astrophysicist and professor

00:00:25.940 --> 00:00:27.860 align:middle line:84%
of science at
Harvard University,

00:00:27.860 --> 00:00:30.500 align:middle line:84%
who discovered the
earliest known object

00:00:30.500 --> 00:00:32.930 align:middle line:84%
from another solar
system to hit Earth.

00:00:32.930 --> 00:00:36.830 align:middle line:10%
>> Over the past five years,
we discovered the first three

00:00:36.830 --> 00:00:38.990 align:middle line:10%
interstellar objects.

00:00:38.990 --> 00:00:40.640 align:middle line:90%
>> Technical assistant Josh.

00:00:40.640 --> 00:00:42.200 align:middle line:90%
Josh, can you pull up the map?

00:00:42.200 --> 00:00:43.000 align:middle line:90%
>> Yeah.

00:00:43.000 --> 00:00:45.530 align:middle line:10%
>> Also joins us to
help set the scenes.

00:00:45.530 --> 00:00:49.490 align:middle line:84%
Join us as we deep dive to
get to the bottom of some

00:00:49.490 --> 00:00:52.820 align:middle line:84%
of the most intriguing
questions of our time.

00:00:52.820 --> 00:00:55.560 align:middle line:84%
>> But the more
evidence you get,

00:00:55.560 --> 00:00:58.820 align:middle line:84%
the more convinced you will
get that it's not natural.

00:00:58.820 --> 00:01:11.870 align:middle line:90%


00:01:11.870 --> 00:01:12.670 align:middle line:90%
>> Hi.

00:01:12.670 --> 00:01:14.050 align:middle line:90%
Welcome to Into the Vortex.

00:01:14.050 --> 00:01:15.250 align:middle line:90%
I'm your host, Jimmy Church.

00:01:15.250 --> 00:01:19.150 align:middle line:84%
And Josh, today we
have Professor Avi Loeb

00:01:19.150 --> 00:01:20.390 align:middle line:90%
of Harvard University.

00:01:20.390 --> 00:01:21.190 align:middle line:90%
Excited.

00:01:21.190 --> 00:01:23.170 align:middle line:84%
>> I am a super fan of
the Galileo Project.

00:01:23.170 --> 00:01:24.370 align:middle line:90%
Happy to have you here, Avi.

00:01:24.370 --> 00:01:27.320 align:middle line:84%
>> Well, thanks for
having me, Jimmy and Josh.

00:01:27.320 --> 00:01:29.740 align:middle line:84%
You may refer to
me as a farm boy.

00:01:29.740 --> 00:01:31.210 align:middle line:90%
>> You don't look farmish.

00:01:31.210 --> 00:01:32.350 align:middle line:90%
>> I grew up on a farm.

00:01:32.350 --> 00:01:34.240 align:middle line:84%
And it pretty much
shaped the way

00:01:34.240 --> 00:01:36.490 align:middle line:84%
I approach everything
in my life.

00:01:36.490 --> 00:01:41.560 align:middle line:84%
>> This is exciting because of
your journey that you've been

00:01:41.560 --> 00:01:43.370 align:middle line:90%
on for a number of years.

00:01:43.370 --> 00:01:46.330 align:middle line:84%
This search for ET and
life in the universe

00:01:46.330 --> 00:01:47.720 align:middle line:90%
didn't happen overnight.

00:01:47.720 --> 00:01:52.570 align:middle line:84%
But how important
is it for academia

00:01:52.570 --> 00:01:55.690 align:middle line:84%
to actually be involved
in the search for ET?

00:01:55.690 --> 00:01:57.520 align:middle line:90%
>> Well, first, let me explain.

00:01:57.520 --> 00:01:59.620 align:middle line:84%
I search for
intelligence from space

00:01:59.620 --> 00:02:02.380 align:middle line:84%
because I don't often
find it here on Earth.

00:02:02.380 --> 00:02:06.010 align:middle line:84%
And that includes in
the academic world,

00:02:06.010 --> 00:02:11.470 align:middle line:84%
there seemed to be a hesitance
in engaging with the subject.

00:02:11.470 --> 00:02:13.810 align:middle line:84%
And I find that
inappropriate given

00:02:13.810 --> 00:02:16.600 align:middle line:84%
that the public is extremely
interested in the question

00:02:16.600 --> 00:02:20.740 align:middle line:84%
of whether there is a smarter
kid on our cosmic block.

00:02:20.740 --> 00:02:26.710 align:middle line:10%
And also, we know now that about
a quarter of the sun-like stars

00:02:26.710 --> 00:02:29.230 align:middle line:10%
have a planet the
size of the Earth,

00:02:29.230 --> 00:02:30.550 align:middle line:10%
roughly at the same separation.

00:02:30.550 --> 00:02:35.440 align:middle line:10%
So the dice of intelligence
was rolled tens of billions

00:02:35.440 --> 00:02:37.900 align:middle line:10%
of times within the
Milky Way galaxy alone.

00:02:37.900 --> 00:02:43.270 align:middle line:84%
It's quite likely that there was
a scientist smarter than Albert

00:02:43.270 --> 00:02:48.500 align:middle line:84%
Einstein who lived on an
exoplanet a billion years ago.

00:02:48.500 --> 00:02:52.780 align:middle line:10%
And the civilization that
benefited from the wisdom

00:02:52.780 --> 00:02:55.360 align:middle line:10%
of that scientist sent probes.

00:02:55.360 --> 00:02:57.258 align:middle line:10%
Within half a billion
years, these probes

00:02:57.258 --> 00:02:59.050 align:middle line:10%
can make it throughout
the Milky Way galaxy

00:02:59.050 --> 00:03:01.600 align:middle line:10%
even if they use
chemical propulsion.

00:03:01.600 --> 00:03:06.670 align:middle line:10%
And then they would settle in
the habitable zones near stars.

00:03:06.670 --> 00:03:09.110 align:middle line:90%
They can replicate themselves.

00:03:09.110 --> 00:03:12.640 align:middle line:84%
And the only way to find out
if we live in such a reality

00:03:12.640 --> 00:03:14.500 align:middle line:90%
is to look out.

00:03:14.500 --> 00:03:17.170 align:middle line:10%
So it sounds straightforward.

00:03:17.170 --> 00:03:20.620 align:middle line:10%
Then on top of that,
over the past five years,

00:03:20.620 --> 00:03:25.690 align:middle line:10%
we discovered the first
three interstellar objects.

00:03:25.690 --> 00:03:29.260 align:middle line:10%
And that was using
astronomical instrumentation.

00:03:29.260 --> 00:03:32.920 align:middle line:10%
And the first two
appear to be weird.

00:03:32.920 --> 00:03:39.430 align:middle line:10%
It's a meteor discovered in
2014, tougher than iron, faster

00:03:39.430 --> 00:03:41.740 align:middle line:10%
than 95% of all the stars.

00:03:41.740 --> 00:03:45.850 align:middle line:10%
And we would like to collect
its fragments because it

00:03:45.850 --> 00:03:47.650 align:middle line:10%
could be artificial in origin.

00:03:47.650 --> 00:03:51.730 align:middle line:10%
And the second was a Oumuamua
more discovered in 2017,

00:03:51.730 --> 00:03:54.010 align:middle line:10%
also didn't look like
a comet or an asteroid,

00:03:54.010 --> 00:03:56.590 align:middle line:10%
was flat, had a weird shape.

00:03:56.590 --> 00:04:01.120 align:middle line:84%
And so my point is nature is
trying to tell us something.

00:04:01.120 --> 00:04:05.440 align:middle line:84%
What's going outside
of the solar system

00:04:05.440 --> 00:04:07.540 align:middle line:84%
is different than
what we expect.

00:04:07.540 --> 00:04:09.760 align:middle line:84%
It's just like going
to your backyard.

00:04:09.760 --> 00:04:11.860 align:middle line:90%
You're used to seeing rocks.

00:04:11.860 --> 00:04:13.990 align:middle line:84%
But every now and
then, you might

00:04:13.990 --> 00:04:19.450 align:middle line:84%
see a tennis ball or a beach
ball that came from a neighbor.

00:04:19.450 --> 00:04:21.700 align:middle line:84%
And that will tell you
that you're not alone

00:04:21.700 --> 00:04:22.900 align:middle line:90%
on this street.

00:04:22.900 --> 00:04:24.340 align:middle line:90%
So we should be open-minded.

00:04:24.340 --> 00:04:28.540 align:middle line:10%
Now you may ask, why is academia
not jumping at the opportunity

00:04:28.540 --> 00:04:29.990 align:middle line:10%
to study these things?

00:04:29.990 --> 00:04:35.140 align:middle line:84%
And the answer is experts
want to pretend that they know

00:04:35.140 --> 00:04:38.950 align:middle line:84%
anything that comes along
based on their past knowledge

00:04:38.950 --> 00:04:41.980 align:middle line:84%
because they get their
honors, awards, recognition,

00:04:41.980 --> 00:04:44.440 align:middle line:84%
their self-esteem out
of their past knowledge.

00:04:44.440 --> 00:04:47.170 align:middle line:84%
They worked hard for
decades acquiring

00:04:47.170 --> 00:04:50.210 align:middle line:84%
the status in the academic
community that they have.

00:04:50.210 --> 00:04:52.270 align:middle line:84%
And so if they're used
to explaining everything

00:04:52.270 --> 00:04:57.310 align:middle line:84%
in the sky, everything in space
as rocks made by nature, then

00:04:57.310 --> 00:04:59.630 align:middle line:84%
when an object comes from
outside the solar system,

00:04:59.630 --> 00:05:02.180 align:middle line:90%
they would say it's a rock.

00:05:02.180 --> 00:05:06.800 align:middle line:10%
To me, it's just like a cave
dweller finding a cell phone.

00:05:06.800 --> 00:05:09.080 align:middle line:84%
The cave dweller would
say it's a rock of a type

00:05:09.080 --> 00:05:11.570 align:middle line:84%
that I've never seen
before, but it's a rock.

00:05:11.570 --> 00:05:15.100 align:middle line:84%
But the more evidence you
get, the more convinced

00:05:15.100 --> 00:05:18.190 align:middle line:84%
you will get that
it's not natural.

00:05:18.190 --> 00:05:20.320 align:middle line:10%
>> In your book,
Extraterrestrial,

00:05:20.320 --> 00:05:23.230 align:middle line:10%
which is an incredible read.

00:05:23.230 --> 00:05:27.280 align:middle line:10%
I have personally, as you know,
read this probably 50 times.

00:05:27.280 --> 00:05:29.950 align:middle line:10%
And every time I
finish the book, I just

00:05:29.950 --> 00:05:33.430 align:middle line:10%
flip it over and
start over again.

00:05:33.430 --> 00:05:35.380 align:middle line:84%
There must have
been for somebody

00:05:35.380 --> 00:05:40.720 align:middle line:84%
like you a certain amount
of pushback from academia.

00:05:40.720 --> 00:05:42.380 align:middle line:90%
How did you deal with that?

00:05:42.380 --> 00:05:47.080 align:middle line:84%
>> Well, between 2011
and 2020, for nine years,

00:05:47.080 --> 00:05:50.680 align:middle line:84%
I was the longest serving
chair of the Harvard University

00:05:50.680 --> 00:05:52.270 align:middle line:90%
Astronomy Department.

00:05:52.270 --> 00:05:56.380 align:middle line:84%
And I also chaired the Board
of Physics and Astronomy

00:05:56.380 --> 00:05:58.780 align:middle line:90%
of the National Academies.

00:05:58.780 --> 00:06:02.350 align:middle line:84%
I'm still the chair of
the Starshot Initiative

00:06:02.350 --> 00:06:05.050 align:middle line:90%
of the Breakthrough Foundation.

00:06:05.050 --> 00:06:08.830 align:middle line:84%
And I'm also the director
of the Institute for Theory

00:06:08.830 --> 00:06:12.370 align:middle line:84%
and Computation and the founding
director of the Black Hole

00:06:12.370 --> 00:06:13.270 align:middle line:90%
Initiative.

00:06:13.270 --> 00:06:16.680 align:middle line:84%
Now all of these
leadership positions

00:06:16.680 --> 00:06:20.850 align:middle line:84%
gave me the confidence
that allows me not

00:06:20.850 --> 00:06:23.460 align:middle line:84%
to pay too much attention
to what other people say,

00:06:23.460 --> 00:06:26.820 align:middle line:84%
but simply do the right
thing based on common sense.

00:06:26.820 --> 00:06:29.400 align:middle line:90%
As I said, I grew up on a farm.

00:06:29.400 --> 00:06:31.230 align:middle line:90%
I pay less attention to people.

00:06:31.230 --> 00:06:35.160 align:middle line:84%
And then in 2017,
Oumuamua came along.

00:06:35.160 --> 00:06:38.640 align:middle line:84%
And it was weird,
so I wrote about it.

00:06:38.640 --> 00:06:40.140 align:middle line:84%
A scientific paper
saying maybe it's

00:06:40.140 --> 00:06:42.660 align:middle line:84%
artificial in origin because
of all the anomalies.

00:06:42.660 --> 00:06:44.140 align:middle line:90%
>> Can you pull that up, Josh?

00:06:44.140 --> 00:06:46.200 align:middle line:84%
Do you have an
image of Oumuamua?

00:06:46.200 --> 00:06:47.395 align:middle line:90%
>> I do.

00:06:47.395 --> 00:06:49.770 align:middle line:84%
I'm worried it's not what Avi
thinks it should look like,

00:06:49.770 --> 00:06:51.500 align:middle line:90%
but here we are.

00:06:51.500 --> 00:06:52.300 align:middle line:10%
>> Yeah.

00:06:52.300 --> 00:06:57.650 align:middle line:10%
So that's the way it should
look like from the side.

00:06:57.650 --> 00:07:00.320 align:middle line:10%
It was at least 10 times
longer than it is wide.

00:07:00.320 --> 00:07:04.670 align:middle line:10%
But think about a piece of
paper tumbling in the wind.

00:07:04.670 --> 00:07:08.300 align:middle line:84%
It would not line
exactly edge on.

00:07:08.300 --> 00:07:12.020 align:middle line:84%
And you might think that
it's actually a cigar, where

00:07:12.020 --> 00:07:13.790 align:middle line:90%
it's in fact a flat object.

00:07:13.790 --> 00:07:16.130 align:middle line:84%
And the best fit
to the reflection

00:07:16.130 --> 00:07:19.820 align:middle line:84%
of sunlight from this
object was of a flat shape,

00:07:19.820 --> 00:07:21.680 align:middle line:90%
pancake-like shape.

00:07:21.680 --> 00:07:24.410 align:middle line:10%
>> Avi, one the things that
confuses me about Oumuamua was

00:07:24.410 --> 00:07:27.110 align:middle line:10%
not just pronouncing it, but
was also how it traveled through

00:07:27.110 --> 00:07:27.910 align:middle line:10%
space.

00:07:27.910 --> 00:07:30.380 align:middle line:84%
I've seen animations where
it spins, or it flips.

00:07:30.380 --> 00:07:32.430 align:middle line:84%
And for some reason,
that matters to me.

00:07:32.430 --> 00:07:34.700 align:middle line:84%
I was wondering if you by
clarity on how it exactly

00:07:34.700 --> 00:07:36.260 align:middle line:90%
moved past Earth.

00:07:36.260 --> 00:07:39.590 align:middle line:10%
>> Well, it was tumbling
every eight hours.

00:07:39.590 --> 00:07:42.770 align:middle line:10%
And the amount of
sunlight reflected from it

00:07:42.770 --> 00:07:45.120 align:middle line:10%
changed by a factor of
10 as it was tumbling.

00:07:45.120 --> 00:07:47.630 align:middle line:84%
So that made it quite
unusual because it

00:07:47.630 --> 00:07:50.510 align:middle line:84%
meant that it had a very
extreme shape, just like a piece

00:07:50.510 --> 00:07:52.340 align:middle line:90%
of paper tumbling in the wind.

00:07:52.340 --> 00:07:56.210 align:middle line:84%
But if you think about it
as an artificial object,

00:07:56.210 --> 00:08:00.800 align:middle line:84%
you might think that it's
trying to look in all directions

00:08:00.800 --> 00:08:04.130 align:middle line:84%
in order to gain some
insight on whether there

00:08:04.130 --> 00:08:07.400 align:middle line:84%
is life in the habitable
region around the sun.

00:08:07.400 --> 00:08:11.150 align:middle line:84%
And it actually passed very
close to the inner planets,

00:08:11.150 --> 00:08:12.200 align:middle line:90%
unusually close.

00:08:12.200 --> 00:08:13.760 align:middle line:10%
We are actually
looking right now

00:08:13.760 --> 00:08:17.660 align:middle line:10%
into the question of whether
the trajectory was designed

00:08:17.660 --> 00:08:19.910 align:middle line:10%
in a very special
way that allowed

00:08:19.910 --> 00:08:22.970 align:middle line:10%
it to pass near all of
the habitable planets

00:08:22.970 --> 00:08:25.850 align:middle line:10%
when they came close to it.

00:08:25.850 --> 00:08:27.540 align:middle line:10%
>> No gravity assist.

00:08:27.540 --> 00:08:28.340 align:middle line:10%
>> No.

00:08:28.340 --> 00:08:32.150 align:middle line:10%
The only thing is that it
exhibited an excess push away

00:08:32.150 --> 00:08:35.600 align:middle line:10%
from the sun without
showing a cometary tail.

00:08:35.600 --> 00:08:38.390 align:middle line:84%
And the question
was what pushed it?

00:08:38.390 --> 00:08:43.130 align:middle line:84%
And we suggest that maybe it's
the reflection of sunlight.

00:08:43.130 --> 00:08:46.340 align:middle line:10%
And then in
September, 2020, there

00:08:46.340 --> 00:08:50.270 align:middle line:10%
was another object that
exhibited an excess push away

00:08:50.270 --> 00:08:52.040 align:middle line:10%
from the sun by
reflecting sunlight.

00:08:52.040 --> 00:08:54.020 align:middle line:90%
No cometary tail.

00:08:54.020 --> 00:08:56.630 align:middle line:84%
And after a few
weeks, the astronomers

00:08:56.630 --> 00:09:00.020 align:middle line:84%
who discovered it with the
same telescope in Hawaii

00:09:00.020 --> 00:09:02.630 align:middle line:84%
realized that it's actually
a rocket booster launched

00:09:02.630 --> 00:09:05.210 align:middle line:90%
in 1966 by NASA.

00:09:05.210 --> 00:09:09.020 align:middle line:84%
And so it had thin
walls, and therefore,

00:09:09.020 --> 00:09:12.290 align:middle line:90%
a large area for its mass.

00:09:12.290 --> 00:09:15.860 align:middle line:84%
And we know that we produced
this object artificially.

00:09:15.860 --> 00:09:19.320 align:middle line:84%
The question is who
produced Oumuamua?

00:09:19.320 --> 00:09:21.140 align:middle line:90%
>> And here's the thing.

00:09:21.140 --> 00:09:25.520 align:middle line:84%
All of the artist's
renderings of Oumuamua

00:09:25.520 --> 00:09:28.370 align:middle line:90%
are just an interpretation.

00:09:28.370 --> 00:09:31.910 align:middle line:84%
We never had any clear
images of Oumuamua.

00:09:31.910 --> 00:09:34.340 align:middle line:10%
So when we look at
an image like this

00:09:34.340 --> 00:09:36.290 align:middle line:10%
or when you see an
image like this,

00:09:36.290 --> 00:09:39.230 align:middle line:10%
I'm sure that you're taken
aback a little bit because this

00:09:39.230 --> 00:09:42.030 align:middle line:10%
doesn't represent at all
with the data has shown us.

00:09:42.030 --> 00:09:42.830 align:middle line:90%
>> Yeah.

00:09:42.830 --> 00:09:45.080 align:middle line:84%
They say a picture is
worth a thousand words.

00:09:45.080 --> 00:09:48.000 align:middle line:10%
In my case, it's
worth 66,000 words,

00:09:48.000 --> 00:09:49.910 align:middle line:10%
the number of words in my book.

00:09:49.910 --> 00:09:52.520 align:middle line:84%
I just want to have
an image of an object

00:09:52.520 --> 00:09:54.590 align:middle line:84%
like that, so that I can
demonstrate my point,

00:09:54.590 --> 00:09:55.700 align:middle line:90%
that it's not a rock.

00:09:55.700 --> 00:09:58.310 align:middle line:84%
When suggesting that it may
be artificial in origin,

00:09:58.310 --> 00:10:01.970 align:middle line:84%
I got a huge amount of
pushback and ridicule

00:10:01.970 --> 00:10:05.390 align:middle line:84%
by some people who
are not necessarily

00:10:05.390 --> 00:10:07.160 align:middle line:90%
practicing scientists.

00:10:07.160 --> 00:10:10.760 align:middle line:90%
That's the strange thing.

00:10:10.760 --> 00:10:13.580 align:middle line:84%
And I was trained up in the
military at a young age.

00:10:13.580 --> 00:10:15.530 align:middle line:84%
I served in the
Israeli military.

00:10:15.530 --> 00:10:19.460 align:middle line:84%
And when during the first
few months as a paratrooper,

00:10:19.460 --> 00:10:22.040 align:middle line:84%
I remember the saying that
sometimes, a soldier has

00:10:22.040 --> 00:10:24.050 align:middle line:84%
to put his body on
the barbed wire,

00:10:24.050 --> 00:10:26.310 align:middle line:84%
so that others
will pass through.

00:10:26.310 --> 00:10:29.660 align:middle line:84%
And so in order to
bring this subject

00:10:29.660 --> 00:10:31.880 align:middle line:84%
to its proper place
in the mainstream,

00:10:31.880 --> 00:10:36.260 align:middle line:84%
I realized that I have to go
through this pain of people

00:10:36.260 --> 00:10:38.120 align:middle line:90%
saying things on social media.

00:10:38.120 --> 00:10:39.470 align:middle line:90%
But I ignore it.

00:10:39.470 --> 00:10:41.510 align:middle line:84%
I have no footprint
on social media.

00:10:41.510 --> 00:10:44.420 align:middle line:84%
And what I pay attention
to is the evidence.

00:10:44.420 --> 00:10:48.170 align:middle line:84%
And the evidence about
Oumuamua looked unusual.

00:10:48.170 --> 00:10:50.870 align:middle line:84%
And the same was true
about this meteor

00:10:50.870 --> 00:10:54.020 align:middle line:84%
that we discovered with
my student, Amir Siraj.

00:10:54.020 --> 00:10:56.990 align:middle line:84%
These were the two
interstellar objects

00:10:56.990 --> 00:11:00.620 align:middle line:84%
that we've discovered
over the past five years.

00:11:00.620 --> 00:11:03.830 align:middle line:84%
And why would the first
two appear so unusual?

00:11:03.830 --> 00:11:07.880 align:middle line:84%
To me, it may imply that
something else is going on

00:11:07.880 --> 00:11:11.430 align:middle line:84%
outside the solar system
that we did not think about.

00:11:11.430 --> 00:11:13.880 align:middle line:84%
And of course, there
is a huge amount

00:11:13.880 --> 00:11:17.100 align:middle line:84%
of pushback against that from
the scientific community.

00:11:17.100 --> 00:11:20.840 align:middle line:84%
But I think that the
more evidence we get,

00:11:20.840 --> 00:11:23.790 align:middle line:84%
the clearer it would become
that we should consider it,

00:11:23.790 --> 00:11:27.830 align:middle line:84%
because this is the
biggest question that

00:11:27.830 --> 00:11:30.380 align:middle line:84%
would affect the
future of humanity,

00:11:30.380 --> 00:11:32.670 align:middle line:84%
if we find that
we are not alone,

00:11:32.670 --> 00:11:36.300 align:middle line:84%
that there is a smarter
intelligence out there.

00:11:36.300 --> 00:11:41.930 align:middle line:84%
And it will change our
aspirations in space.

00:11:41.930 --> 00:11:44.840 align:middle line:84%
A very advanced,
scientific civilization

00:11:44.840 --> 00:11:47.480 align:middle line:84%
is a good approximation
to God if you

00:11:47.480 --> 00:11:50.540 align:middle line:84%
think about it because it could
create life in the laboratory.

00:11:50.540 --> 00:11:53.120 align:middle line:84%
It could even perhaps
create a baby universe

00:11:53.120 --> 00:11:53.930 align:middle line:90%
in the laboratory.

00:11:53.930 --> 00:11:57.530 align:middle line:84%
All these attributes that
appear in religious texts

00:11:57.530 --> 00:11:59.840 align:middle line:84%
in association with
God could relate

00:11:59.840 --> 00:12:03.380 align:middle line:84%
to a civilization that
is a million years more

00:12:03.380 --> 00:12:05.930 align:middle line:84%
advanced than we are in
science and technology.

00:12:05.930 --> 00:12:10.700 align:middle line:84%
And so finding out if such
a thing exists out there,

00:12:10.700 --> 00:12:16.220 align:middle line:84%
discovering the unknown is
similar to spirituality.

00:12:16.220 --> 00:12:22.780 align:middle line:84%
Trying to explore the
unknown is giving us

00:12:22.780 --> 00:12:25.450 align:middle line:90%
a meaning to our lives.

00:12:25.450 --> 00:12:32.280 align:middle line:84%
>> With Oumuamua, what I always
found extremely interesting is

00:12:32.280 --> 00:12:39.220 align:middle line:84%
that the data said one thing,
but the professionals out there

00:12:39.220 --> 00:12:43.080 align:middle line:84%
tried to make that data
fit their opinions.

00:12:43.080 --> 00:12:48.750 align:middle line:84%
They tried to make it fit
into some natural cosmic event

00:12:48.750 --> 00:12:51.610 align:middle line:84%
when the data represented
something completely different.

00:12:51.610 --> 00:12:53.850 align:middle line:84%
We're talking about
a craft that seemed

00:12:53.850 --> 00:12:57.600 align:middle line:84%
to be under intelligent
control, was turning on its own,

00:12:57.600 --> 00:13:03.150 align:middle line:84%
was increasing its speed, didn't
have any means of propulsion.

00:13:03.150 --> 00:13:04.860 align:middle line:90%
It wasn't gravity-assisted.

00:13:04.860 --> 00:13:06.270 align:middle line:90%
All of these things.

00:13:06.270 --> 00:13:11.340 align:middle line:84%
But academia tried to
force their belief system

00:13:11.340 --> 00:13:13.750 align:middle line:90%
into data that didn't work.

00:13:13.750 --> 00:13:19.590 align:middle line:84%
And that's what the book was
about, was this conflict.

00:13:19.590 --> 00:13:21.870 align:middle line:84%
And by you presenting
the conflict,

00:13:21.870 --> 00:13:24.490 align:middle line:90%
does that create more problems?

00:13:24.490 --> 00:13:25.290 align:middle line:90%
>> Yeah.

00:13:25.290 --> 00:13:28.170 align:middle line:84%
So at first, the
mainstream astronomer

00:13:28.170 --> 00:13:31.230 align:middle line:90%
said it must be natural.

00:13:31.230 --> 00:13:34.590 align:middle line:84%
And then they started to come
up with natural objects that

00:13:34.590 --> 00:13:36.870 align:middle line:84%
might explain the
anomalies of Oumuamua.

00:13:36.870 --> 00:13:40.430 align:middle line:90%
For example, a dust bunny.

00:13:40.430 --> 00:13:44.640 align:middle line:84%
A cloud of dust particles
that is very loosely bound,

00:13:44.640 --> 00:13:46.680 align:middle line:90%
100 times less dense than air.

00:13:46.680 --> 00:13:52.260 align:middle line:84%
So that by reflecting sunlight,
it gets pushed like a feather.

00:13:52.260 --> 00:13:55.950 align:middle line:84%
The problem with that is it
won't maintain its integrity.

00:13:55.950 --> 00:13:59.430 align:middle line:84%
It will be heated up
to hundreds of degrees

00:13:59.430 --> 00:14:02.580 align:middle line:84%
and will not survive the
journey near the sun.

00:14:02.580 --> 00:14:04.470 align:middle line:84%
And then there was
another suggestion.

00:14:04.470 --> 00:14:08.110 align:middle line:84%
OK, so maybe it's a
chunk of frozen hydrogen.

00:14:08.110 --> 00:14:10.050 align:middle line:84%
And when the
hydrogen evaporates,

00:14:10.050 --> 00:14:12.420 align:middle line:84%
it behaves just
like a comet, but we

00:14:12.420 --> 00:14:14.580 align:middle line:84%
can't see it because
hydrogen is transparent.

00:14:14.580 --> 00:14:17.370 align:middle line:84%
The problem with that is it
won't survive the journey

00:14:17.370 --> 00:14:18.300 align:middle line:90%
in interstellar space.

00:14:18.300 --> 00:14:20.920 align:middle line:84%
Hydrogen would
evaporate very quickly.

00:14:20.920 --> 00:14:25.110 align:middle line:84%
And so when that group of people
who suggested the hydrogen

00:14:25.110 --> 00:14:28.710 align:middle line:84%
iceberg realized that after
we wrote a paper about it,

00:14:28.710 --> 00:14:31.080 align:middle line:84%
then there was another
team that suggested maybe

00:14:31.080 --> 00:14:32.640 align:middle line:90%
it's a nitrogen iceberg.

00:14:32.640 --> 00:14:35.670 align:middle line:84%
A chunk of frozen nitrogen
chipped off the surface

00:14:35.670 --> 00:14:37.200 align:middle line:90%
of a planet like Pluto.

00:14:37.200 --> 00:14:40.920 align:middle line:84%
And there, the problem is there
is not enough frozen nitrogen

00:14:40.920 --> 00:14:42.690 align:middle line:84%
in the Milky Way
galaxy to produce

00:14:42.690 --> 00:14:45.150 align:middle line:90%
a population of such chips.

00:14:45.150 --> 00:14:49.170 align:middle line:84%
So all of these suggestions
have problems, but all of them

00:14:49.170 --> 00:14:52.810 align:middle line:84%
also talk about something
that we've never seen before.

00:14:52.810 --> 00:14:55.080 align:middle line:84%
We don't know if
nature makes a dust

00:14:55.080 --> 00:14:58.780 align:middle line:84%
bunny, if nature makes a
hydrogen iceberg or a nitrogen

00:14:58.780 --> 00:14:59.580 align:middle line:90%
iceberg.

00:14:59.580 --> 00:15:03.420 align:middle line:84%
Yet these are the possibilities
that the astronomy community

00:15:03.420 --> 00:15:09.900 align:middle line:84%
embraced just because they
allowed a natural explanation

00:15:09.900 --> 00:15:11.730 align:middle line:84%
to all the anomalies
of Oumuamua.

00:15:11.730 --> 00:15:16.260 align:middle line:84%
And I say if it's
an object of a type

00:15:16.260 --> 00:15:17.970 align:middle line:84%
that we've never seen
before, we should

00:15:17.970 --> 00:15:20.400 align:middle line:84%
allow for the possibility
that it's artificial.

00:15:20.400 --> 00:15:22.560 align:middle line:84%
>> Well, was that
the mistake though?

00:15:22.560 --> 00:15:28.440 align:middle line:84%
The mistake of being asleep
when Oumuamua was here,

00:15:28.440 --> 00:15:31.050 align:middle line:84%
didn't have the opportunity
to capture the data.

00:15:31.050 --> 00:15:32.430 align:middle line:90%
It was here.

00:15:32.430 --> 00:15:34.740 align:middle line:84%
We only had 11
days to observe it.

00:15:34.740 --> 00:15:35.830 align:middle line:90%
It's now gone.

00:15:35.830 --> 00:15:39.720 align:middle line:84%
We will never collect
more data on Oumuamua.

00:15:39.720 --> 00:15:41.520 align:middle line:90%
That's an impossibility.

00:15:41.520 --> 00:15:44.040 align:middle line:84%
And now, we have
the Galileo Project,

00:15:44.040 --> 00:15:47.070 align:middle line:84%
which is primed and ready
to go if an event like this

00:15:47.070 --> 00:15:47.910 align:middle line:90%
happens again.

00:15:47.910 --> 00:15:48.710 align:middle line:90%
>> Right.

00:15:48.710 --> 00:15:51.030 align:middle line:84%
And we also have
a dating app now,

00:15:51.030 --> 00:15:53.370 align:middle line:84%
the Vera Rubin
Observatory in Chile, that

00:15:53.370 --> 00:15:56.130 align:middle line:90%
will start operations in 2023.

00:15:56.130 --> 00:15:58.890 align:middle line:84%
And it could
identify more objects

00:15:58.890 --> 00:16:00.960 align:middle line:84%
like Oumuamua that
look weird unlike,

00:16:00.960 --> 00:16:05.080 align:middle line:84%
a comet or an asteroid that are
familiar from the solar system.

00:16:05.080 --> 00:16:08.850 align:middle line:84%
And I call it a dating
app because if we identify

00:16:08.850 --> 00:16:13.120 align:middle line:84%
an object that is worth
rendezvousing with,

00:16:13.120 --> 00:16:16.270 align:middle line:84%
we could spend $1,000,000,000
on a space mission

00:16:16.270 --> 00:16:19.090 align:middle line:84%
that will come close to it and
take a close up photograph.

00:16:19.090 --> 00:16:21.850 align:middle line:84%
And that's part of the activity
within the Galileo Project.

00:16:21.850 --> 00:16:23.870 align:middle line:90%
Designing such a mission.

00:16:23.870 --> 00:16:26.080 align:middle line:84%
And we also have
the Webb telescope

00:16:26.080 --> 00:16:29.110 align:middle line:84%
that can look at such an object
from a different direction

00:16:29.110 --> 00:16:31.360 align:middle line:90%
than the observatories on Earth.

00:16:31.360 --> 00:16:33.700 align:middle line:84%
And then can, in
principle, figure out

00:16:33.700 --> 00:16:36.280 align:middle line:84%
the motion of this object
in three dimensions

00:16:36.280 --> 00:16:40.150 align:middle line:84%
and tell us whether
it has propulsion

00:16:40.150 --> 00:16:43.390 align:middle line:84%
that is different
than the rocket effect

00:16:43.390 --> 00:16:45.070 align:middle line:90%
from cometary evaporation.

00:16:45.070 --> 00:16:48.020 align:middle line:84%
And it could also tell us the
composition of the object.

00:16:48.020 --> 00:16:51.190 align:middle line:84%
So now that we are alert
to this possibility,

00:16:51.190 --> 00:16:54.670 align:middle line:84%
we could find much more
about the next Oumuamua.

00:16:54.670 --> 00:16:57.100 align:middle line:90%
>> Oumuamua, of course, 2017.

00:16:57.100 --> 00:17:00.640 align:middle line:84%
And there was a lot of
extraordinary things in the UAP

00:17:00.640 --> 00:17:03.503 align:middle line:84%
UFO community that
happened over that period

00:17:03.503 --> 00:17:04.420 align:middle line:90%
of a couple of months.

00:17:04.420 --> 00:17:05.859 align:middle line:90%
It was a pretty exciting time.

00:17:05.859 --> 00:17:09.190 align:middle line:84%
But in 2014, the
Department of Defense

00:17:09.190 --> 00:17:12.099 align:middle line:84%
and other agencies here
in the United States

00:17:12.099 --> 00:17:17.290 align:middle line:84%
monitored an object apparently
from interstellar space entered

00:17:17.290 --> 00:17:20.360 align:middle line:84%
our atmosphere and is somewhere
in the vicinity of Papua New

00:17:20.360 --> 00:17:21.160 align:middle line:90%
Guinea.

00:17:21.160 --> 00:17:25.180 align:middle line:84%
And this is your next project,
in addition to, of course,

00:17:25.180 --> 00:17:26.050 align:middle line:90%
Galileo.

00:17:26.050 --> 00:17:26.850 align:middle line:90%
>> Right.

00:17:26.850 --> 00:17:30.460 align:middle line:84%
So aside from objects that
reflect sunlight and pass

00:17:30.460 --> 00:17:33.550 align:middle line:84%
near the Earth, we
have an opportunity

00:17:33.550 --> 00:17:36.250 align:middle line:84%
of using the Earth
as a fishing net.

00:17:36.250 --> 00:17:40.840 align:middle line:84%
It could collide with an object
along its path around the sun.

00:17:40.840 --> 00:17:45.640 align:middle line:84%
And the advantage of that is
that when an object burns up

00:17:45.640 --> 00:17:49.270 align:middle line:84%
in the atmosphere of the
Earth, it shines very brightly,

00:17:49.270 --> 00:17:52.180 align:middle line:84%
so we could, in principle,
see much smaller objects

00:17:52.180 --> 00:17:53.110 align:middle line:90%
than Oumuamua.

00:17:53.110 --> 00:17:55.750 align:middle line:84%
Oumuamua was the size
of a football field.

00:17:55.750 --> 00:18:00.730 align:middle line:84%
And this meteor from 2014 that
the government missile warning

00:18:00.730 --> 00:18:06.790 align:middle line:84%
systems identified was roughly
the size of a watermelon.

00:18:06.790 --> 00:18:09.700 align:middle line:84%
And we didn't see it because
of the reflection of sunlight.

00:18:09.700 --> 00:18:13.450 align:middle line:84%
We saw it because it burned
up in the Earth's atmosphere.

00:18:13.450 --> 00:18:16.810 align:middle line:84%
And it was very different
than Oumuamua in the sense

00:18:16.810 --> 00:18:19.360 align:middle line:90%
that it was tougher than iron.

00:18:19.360 --> 00:18:22.540 align:middle line:84%
We know from the light
curve that the government

00:18:22.540 --> 00:18:26.780 align:middle line:84%
released that it burned only
in the lower Earth atmosphere.

00:18:26.780 --> 00:18:31.300 align:middle line:84%
And as a result, it was
subjected to extreme stress

00:18:31.300 --> 00:18:33.460 align:middle line:90%
from the atmosphere.

00:18:33.460 --> 00:18:37.360 align:middle line:84%
And it must have been
very tough, tougher

00:18:37.360 --> 00:18:42.280 align:middle line:84%
than 273 of all other meteors
in the government catalog.

00:18:42.280 --> 00:18:47.050 align:middle line:84%
And so it was an outlier in
terms of its composition.

00:18:47.050 --> 00:18:48.520 align:middle line:90%
Tougher than iron.

00:18:48.520 --> 00:18:51.910 align:middle line:84%
And also, it was
moving faster than 95%

00:18:51.910 --> 00:18:54.790 align:middle line:84%
of all the stars in
the vicinity of the sun

00:18:54.790 --> 00:18:56.110 align:middle line:90%
outside the solar system.

00:18:56.110 --> 00:18:59.920 align:middle line:84%
So it could have
been a spacecraft.

00:18:59.920 --> 00:19:03.640 align:middle line:84%
If you imagine the New
Horizons spacecraft,

00:19:03.640 --> 00:19:06.640 align:middle line:84%
that is making its way
out of the solar system,

00:19:06.640 --> 00:19:11.020 align:middle line:84%
a billion years from now
colliding with an exoplanet.

00:19:11.020 --> 00:19:15.070 align:middle line:84%
And the astronomers
there saying, oh,

00:19:15.070 --> 00:19:17.050 align:middle line:90%
look at this meteor.

00:19:17.050 --> 00:19:21.400 align:middle line:84%
And some astronomers
say, oh, forget about it.

00:19:21.400 --> 00:19:22.990 align:middle line:90%
It's just a rock.

00:19:22.990 --> 00:19:27.760 align:middle line:84%
But others are curious enough
to check the ocean floor where

00:19:27.760 --> 00:19:31.570 align:middle line:84%
the fragments landed and
realized that it was actually

00:19:31.570 --> 00:19:36.040 align:middle line:84%
made of an alloy and not
a rock, rocky material.

00:19:36.040 --> 00:19:39.500 align:middle line:10%
And moreover, in the case of
the New Horizons spacecraft,

00:19:39.500 --> 00:19:42.940 align:middle line:10%
they would find
perhaps this small box

00:19:42.940 --> 00:19:45.580 align:middle line:10%
that was attached
to it that included

00:19:45.580 --> 00:19:51.370 align:middle line:10%
30 grams of the ashes of Clyde
Tombaugh, the scientist who

00:19:51.370 --> 00:19:53.480 align:middle line:10%
discovered Pluto.

00:19:53.480 --> 00:19:57.350 align:middle line:84%
And they would say, well,
that makes little sense

00:19:57.350 --> 00:20:02.240 align:middle line:84%
because these ashes are just
like the ashes of a cigarette.

00:20:02.240 --> 00:20:03.720 align:middle line:90%
They contain no information.

00:20:03.720 --> 00:20:09.080 align:middle line:84%
So these humans burned up
the genetic information

00:20:09.080 --> 00:20:11.480 align:middle line:84%
about a person that they
wanted to commemorate.

00:20:11.480 --> 00:20:13.800 align:middle line:84%
And therefore, they
must be very aggressive.

00:20:13.800 --> 00:20:15.740 align:middle line:84%
They have these
primitive rituals.

00:20:15.740 --> 00:20:17.960 align:middle line:84%
We don't want anything
to do with these humans.

00:20:17.960 --> 00:20:20.360 align:middle line:84%
>> You know, when
they arrive, Avi,

00:20:20.360 --> 00:20:23.510 align:middle line:84%
they're going to
ask for you first.

00:20:23.510 --> 00:20:28.280 align:middle line:84%
The difference in data
from what a university

00:20:28.280 --> 00:20:31.250 align:middle line:84%
or professional organization
would collect it's

00:20:31.250 --> 00:20:33.740 align:middle line:84%
obviously different from
eyewitness testimony

00:20:33.740 --> 00:20:35.750 align:middle line:90%
that we've had for decades.

00:20:35.750 --> 00:20:38.510 align:middle line:84%
But you've just
mentioned evidence

00:20:38.510 --> 00:20:40.550 align:middle line:90%
a couple of times and data.

00:20:40.550 --> 00:20:42.320 align:middle line:90%
What evidence is there?

00:20:42.320 --> 00:20:44.570 align:middle line:90%
What do you consider evidence?

00:20:44.570 --> 00:20:48.770 align:middle line:84%
And how would that be different
from a cell phone video

00:20:48.770 --> 00:20:52.020 align:middle line:84%
from somebody that is just
seeing something in the sky?

00:20:52.020 --> 00:20:52.820 align:middle line:90%
>> Right.

00:20:52.820 --> 00:20:56.480 align:middle line:84%
So let me start by saying
that I grew up on a farm.

00:20:56.480 --> 00:21:00.740 align:middle line:84%
And I was attached to nature,
much more than to people.

00:21:00.740 --> 00:21:03.230 align:middle line:84%
I distinguish between the two
because people can tell you

00:21:03.230 --> 00:21:05.160 align:middle line:90%
stories that are not real.

00:21:05.160 --> 00:21:08.040 align:middle line:90%
They have some hidden agenda.

00:21:08.040 --> 00:21:13.720 align:middle line:84%
And so I would like to advance
my knowledge based on evidence,

00:21:13.720 --> 00:21:16.950 align:middle line:84%
based on clues that we collect
directly from nature, not

00:21:16.950 --> 00:21:18.780 align:middle line:90%
through the filter of people.

00:21:18.780 --> 00:21:22.830 align:middle line:84%
And when people use
their cell phones,

00:21:22.830 --> 00:21:25.350 align:middle line:84%
they usually have a camera
that has an aperture

00:21:25.350 --> 00:21:26.590 align:middle line:90%
of only a few millimeters.

00:21:26.590 --> 00:21:27.510 align:middle line:90%
So it's very small.

00:21:27.510 --> 00:21:31.020 align:middle line:84%
And the images are quite fuzzy
when you look at an object

00:21:31.020 --> 00:21:32.580 align:middle line:90%
several miles away.

00:21:32.580 --> 00:21:35.130 align:middle line:84%
And that's just
the laws of optics.

00:21:35.130 --> 00:21:36.520 align:middle line:90%
You can't improve on that.

00:21:36.520 --> 00:21:39.450 align:middle line:84%
The only way to improve is
to get a bigger aperture,

00:21:39.450 --> 00:21:42.790 align:middle line:84%
like a telescope, and look
at the object and resolve it.

00:21:42.790 --> 00:21:47.390 align:middle line:84%
And if you see a label made
on exoplanet so-and-so, then

00:21:47.390 --> 00:21:49.860 align:middle line:84%
you know that it's
not from this Earth.

00:21:49.860 --> 00:21:53.050 align:middle line:84%
Now the government says
they have high quality data,

00:21:53.050 --> 00:21:54.690 align:middle line:90%
but it's classified.

00:21:54.690 --> 00:21:58.500 align:middle line:84%
And people who looked at that
say that is a serious matter.

00:21:58.500 --> 00:22:00.930 align:middle line:84%
However, waiting
for the government

