And therefore, since the
sky is not classified,

00:22:12.300 --> 00:22:15.510 align:middle line:84%
I would like to get my
own data as a scientist.

00:22:15.510 --> 00:22:17.110 align:middle line:90%
That's the way to make progress.

00:22:17.110 --> 00:22:19.540 align:middle line:84%
And once the data
is good enough,

00:22:19.540 --> 00:22:22.000 align:middle line:84%
it will be impossible
to avoid it.

00:22:22.000 --> 00:22:26.160 align:middle line:84%
So for example, if you
go back for centuries,

00:22:26.160 --> 00:22:28.590 align:middle line:84%
Galileo Galilei looked
through his telescope

00:22:28.590 --> 00:22:31.500 align:middle line:84%
and realized, oh,
maybe the Earth is not

00:22:31.500 --> 00:22:33.000 align:middle line:90%
at the center of the universe.

00:22:33.000 --> 00:22:35.550 align:middle line:90%
He was ridiculed.

00:22:35.550 --> 00:22:40.050 align:middle line:84%
Philosophers at the time
put him in house arrest.

00:22:40.050 --> 00:22:43.050 align:middle line:84%
Today, he would have been
canceled on social media.

00:22:43.050 --> 00:22:47.430 align:middle line:84%
That didn't change the fact that
the Earth moves around the sun.

00:22:47.430 --> 00:22:50.610 align:middle line:90%
Reality is whatever it is.

00:22:50.610 --> 00:22:53.430 align:middle line:84%
If you were to ask these
philosophers to design a space

00:22:53.430 --> 00:22:55.680 align:middle line:84%
mission that would
reach Mars, they

00:22:55.680 --> 00:22:57.360 align:middle line:84%
would never get
to the destination

00:22:57.360 --> 00:23:00.300 align:middle line:84%
because they thought that
Mars moves around the Earth.

00:23:00.300 --> 00:23:06.600 align:middle line:84%
And so people can have presence
on social media or on campuses

00:23:06.600 --> 00:23:08.820 align:middle line:84%
and ridicule one
thing or another.

00:23:08.820 --> 00:23:10.490 align:middle line:90%
That's irrelevant.

00:23:10.490 --> 00:23:11.850 align:middle line:90%
Nature is whatever it is.

00:23:11.850 --> 00:23:14.120 align:middle line:84%
And the only way
for us to find out

00:23:14.120 --> 00:23:16.350 align:middle line:84%
is to get more
evidence, more data.

00:23:16.350 --> 00:23:21.823 align:middle line:84%
But if you keep saying that this
subject is not worth studying,

00:23:21.823 --> 00:23:23.240 align:middle line:84%
then you will never
get that data.

00:23:23.240 --> 00:23:25.070 align:middle line:84%
It's like a
self-fulfilling prophecy.

00:23:25.070 --> 00:23:27.740 align:middle line:84%
If you keep saying everything
in the sky must be natural,

00:23:27.740 --> 00:23:32.030 align:middle line:84%
cannot be artificial unless we
have extraordinary evidence,

00:23:32.030 --> 00:23:33.500 align:middle line:90%
well, guess what?

00:23:33.500 --> 00:23:37.940 align:middle line:84%
People often quote Carl Sagan
as saying extraordinary claims

00:23:37.940 --> 00:23:39.920 align:middle line:90%
require extraordinary evidence.

00:23:39.920 --> 00:23:44.310 align:middle line:84%
I say extraordinary evidence
requires extraordinary funding.

00:23:44.310 --> 00:23:47.660 align:middle line:84%
You have to look for
the evidence actively.

00:23:47.660 --> 00:23:49.520 align:middle line:84%
Just as an example,
we don't know

00:23:49.520 --> 00:23:52.250 align:middle line:84%
what most of the matter
in the universe is.

00:23:52.250 --> 00:23:56.360 align:middle line:84%
In 1933, Fritz Zwicky,
an astronomer at Caltech,

00:23:56.360 --> 00:24:00.030 align:middle line:84%
argued that it's of
unknown substance.

00:24:00.030 --> 00:24:03.340 align:middle line:84%
We don't see that substance
in the solar system.

00:24:03.340 --> 00:24:05.220 align:middle line:90%
And so it's called dark matter.

00:24:05.220 --> 00:24:08.910 align:middle line:84%
And we've invested billions
of dollars, most recently,

00:24:08.910 --> 00:24:11.280 align:middle line:84%
in the context of the
Large Hadron Collider,

00:24:11.280 --> 00:24:13.410 align:middle line:84%
smashing particles
at high energies,

00:24:13.410 --> 00:24:16.990 align:middle line:84%
trying to see if the dark
matter particles are produced.

00:24:16.990 --> 00:24:18.940 align:middle line:10%
We didn't find them.

00:24:18.940 --> 00:24:23.850 align:middle line:10%
So if we will invest billions
of over the next few decades

00:24:23.850 --> 00:24:27.180 align:middle line:10%
in the search for equipment
from other civilizations,

00:24:27.180 --> 00:24:30.750 align:middle line:10%
just because we send
out spacecraft to space

00:24:30.750 --> 00:24:32.700 align:middle line:10%
that will go out of
the solar system,

00:24:32.700 --> 00:24:36.360 align:middle line:10%
and we know of tens of
billions of other planets

00:24:36.360 --> 00:24:38.850 align:middle line:10%
within the Milky
Way who could have

00:24:38.850 --> 00:24:41.828 align:middle line:10%
had intelligent life on them.

00:24:41.828 --> 00:24:43.870 align:middle line:84%
And that could have happened
a billion years ago.

00:24:43.870 --> 00:24:48.000 align:middle line:84%
So perhaps, there is
something in our backyard.

00:24:48.000 --> 00:24:49.260 align:middle line:90%
That all makes sense.

00:24:49.260 --> 00:24:52.050 align:middle line:10%
If we do that search
and not find anything

00:24:52.050 --> 00:24:54.330 align:middle line:10%
despite the billions of
dollars that we invested,

00:24:54.330 --> 00:24:56.640 align:middle line:10%
we would be at
exactly the same point

00:24:56.640 --> 00:24:59.640 align:middle line:10%
as dark matter
searches are right now.

00:24:59.640 --> 00:25:01.800 align:middle line:10%
And they are part of the
mainstream of science.

00:25:01.800 --> 00:25:04.500 align:middle line:10%
So that's why we establish the
Galileo Project, where we are

00:25:04.500 --> 00:25:06.900 align:middle line:10%
funded by private donations.

00:25:06.900 --> 00:25:09.110 align:middle line:84%
And we will go ahead
and collect the data,

00:25:09.110 --> 00:25:10.680 align:middle line:90%
make it open to the public.

00:25:10.680 --> 00:25:13.290 align:middle line:84%
The analysis will
be transparent.

00:25:13.290 --> 00:25:16.890 align:middle line:84%
And hopefully, we'll
know what's out there.

00:25:16.890 --> 00:25:19.200 align:middle line:84%
>> The team has
been put together.

00:25:19.200 --> 00:25:25.620 align:middle line:84%
And just recently, you've
installed collection equipment

00:25:25.620 --> 00:25:27.240 align:middle line:90%
on a rooftop at Harvard.

00:25:27.240 --> 00:25:29.490 align:middle line:90%
Josh, can you pull this up?

00:25:29.490 --> 00:25:32.970 align:middle line:84%
And as we take a
look at this, Avi,

00:25:32.970 --> 00:25:36.450 align:middle line:84%
what instruments
are you using here,

00:25:36.450 --> 00:25:38.520 align:middle line:90%
and what do you expect to find?

00:25:38.520 --> 00:25:42.660 align:middle line:84%
>> Well, we're trying to
take a video of the sky

00:25:42.660 --> 00:25:48.000 align:middle line:84%
in the infrared, in the
optical band, in the radio,

00:25:48.000 --> 00:25:54.060 align:middle line:84%
and also in audio, so that we
can trace objects in the sky.

00:25:54.060 --> 00:25:57.240 align:middle line:84%
And the idea is
to figure out what

00:25:57.240 --> 00:25:59.940 align:middle line:84%
are these mysterious objects
that the government is talking

00:25:59.940 --> 00:26:08.910 align:middle line:84%
about as aerospace, transmedium
objects of unidentified nature.

00:26:08.910 --> 00:26:14.220 align:middle line:84%
In November, 2021,
I attended the forum

00:26:14.220 --> 00:26:15.720 align:middle line:84%
at the Washington
National Cathedral

00:26:15.720 --> 00:26:19.230 align:middle line:84%
with the Director of National
Intelligence Avril Haines.

00:26:19.230 --> 00:26:23.250 align:middle line:84%
And I was sitting
next to her and asking

00:26:23.250 --> 00:26:27.300 align:middle line:84%
her, what's your gut feeling,
because she delivered a report

00:26:27.300 --> 00:26:29.100 align:middle line:90%
to Congress at the time.

00:26:29.100 --> 00:26:31.380 align:middle line:84%
And what's your
gut feeling about

00:26:31.380 --> 00:26:33.000 align:middle line:90%
these unidentified objects?

00:26:33.000 --> 00:26:34.920 align:middle line:90%
And she said, I don't know.

00:26:34.920 --> 00:26:37.440 align:middle line:84%
And she was educated
as a physicist.

00:26:37.440 --> 00:26:40.417 align:middle line:84%
So I say let's help the
government figuring it out

00:26:40.417 --> 00:26:42.750 align:middle line:84%
because the government is not
a scientific organization.

00:26:42.750 --> 00:26:45.990 align:middle line:84%
It's worried mostly
about national security

00:26:45.990 --> 00:26:48.870 align:middle line:84%
and about the safety
of military personnel.

00:26:48.870 --> 00:26:52.770 align:middle line:84%
But scientists can
address everything else.

00:26:52.770 --> 00:26:57.220 align:middle line:84%
And if these objects are
not human-made or natural,

00:26:57.220 --> 00:27:00.600 align:middle line:84%
we can figure out their nature
by taking high resolution

00:27:00.600 --> 00:27:05.400 align:middle line:84%
images or monitoring
their motion in the sky.

00:27:05.400 --> 00:27:09.990 align:middle line:84%
To do that, we need to observe
these objects in the infrared,

00:27:09.990 --> 00:27:12.780 align:middle line:84%
in the optical band,
radio, and audio,

00:27:12.780 --> 00:27:17.490 align:middle line:84%
and then feed the data to
artificial intelligence

00:27:17.490 --> 00:27:21.150 align:middle line:84%
algorithms that will
identify objects,

00:27:21.150 --> 00:27:23.400 align:middle line:84%
and we will use
machine learning,

00:27:23.400 --> 00:27:25.170 align:middle line:90%
learn from experience.

00:27:25.170 --> 00:27:27.450 align:middle line:84%
And basically, there
will be two baskets

00:27:27.450 --> 00:27:30.840 align:middle line:84%
that will include most of
the objects that we see.

00:27:30.840 --> 00:27:36.300 align:middle line:84%
One of them is natural objects,
like birds, bugs, lightnings,

00:27:36.300 --> 00:27:37.530 align:middle line:90%
meteors.

00:27:37.530 --> 00:27:40.740 align:middle line:84%
The second would be
human-made objects,

00:27:40.740 --> 00:27:42.660 align:middle line:90%
like drones, airplanes.

00:27:42.660 --> 00:27:45.510 align:middle line:84%
And the question is is
there something else,

00:27:45.510 --> 00:27:47.970 align:middle line:90%
and is it out of this Earth?

00:27:47.970 --> 00:27:51.038 align:middle line:84%
So the government
says we see things

00:27:51.038 --> 00:27:52.080 align:middle line:90%
that we don't understand.

00:27:52.080 --> 00:27:55.200 align:middle line:84%
And they would never come
out if they had the suspicion

00:27:55.200 --> 00:27:59.400 align:middle line:84%
that it's an adversary because
that's part of their day job,

00:27:59.400 --> 00:28:01.590 align:middle line:84%
to figure out what the
adversaries are doing.

00:28:01.590 --> 00:28:04.440 align:middle line:84%
But they go to
Congress and say, there

00:28:04.440 --> 00:28:08.340 align:middle line:84%
is something else that doesn't
belong to those nations.

00:28:08.340 --> 00:28:10.090 align:middle line:84%
And so the question
is what is it?

00:28:10.090 --> 00:28:13.270 align:middle line:84%
And if it's out
of this Earth, it

00:28:13.270 --> 00:28:15.970 align:middle line:84%
doesn't adhere to
national borders,

00:28:15.970 --> 00:28:19.120 align:middle line:84%
it should be the
subject of science

00:28:19.120 --> 00:28:20.680 align:middle line:84%
because science
is international.

00:28:20.680 --> 00:28:24.130 align:middle line:84%
Science is all about sharing
our knowledge in open fashion.

00:28:24.130 --> 00:28:28.630 align:middle line:84%
Government is about protecting
the nation against threats.

00:28:28.630 --> 00:28:31.570 align:middle line:84%
It's about classifying
information such

00:28:31.570 --> 00:28:33.470 align:middle line:84%
that adversaries will
not be aware of it.

00:28:33.470 --> 00:28:35.440 align:middle line:84%
So there is a
difference in the way

00:28:35.440 --> 00:28:40.450 align:middle line:84%
that the scientific approach
is applied to such questions.

00:28:40.450 --> 00:28:45.460 align:middle line:84%
>> Are you prepared for a
discovery, the high res image,

00:28:45.460 --> 00:28:48.220 align:middle line:84%
something absolutely
extraordinary,

00:28:48.220 --> 00:28:53.350 align:middle line:84%
and then the government coming
in, running a block on this

00:28:53.350 --> 00:28:57.250 align:middle line:84%
and saying this is in the
interests of national security.

00:28:57.250 --> 00:28:59.620 align:middle line:84%
We're taking control
of this data.

00:28:59.620 --> 00:29:02.440 align:middle line:84%
Are you prepared for that, and
what have you thought about it?

00:29:02.440 --> 00:29:04.190 align:middle line:10%
>> I'm not worried
about it at all

00:29:04.190 --> 00:29:07.270 align:middle line:10%
because if it's of
extraterrestrial origin,

00:29:07.270 --> 00:29:12.190 align:middle line:10%
it's not a threat to the
United States in particular.

00:29:12.190 --> 00:29:15.160 align:middle line:84%
It's a subject that
should be dealt

00:29:15.160 --> 00:29:19.010 align:middle line:90%
with by humanity as a whole.

00:29:19.010 --> 00:29:22.690 align:middle line:84%
And my hope is that by
recognizing a smarter kid

00:29:22.690 --> 00:29:27.040 align:middle line:84%
on our block, we will treat
each other as equal members

00:29:27.040 --> 00:29:30.760 align:middle line:84%
of the human species because
the differences among us

00:29:30.760 --> 00:29:34.750 align:middle line:84%
will be meaningless relative
to the technological gap

00:29:34.750 --> 00:29:37.270 align:middle line:90%
between us and them.

00:29:37.270 --> 00:29:40.420 align:middle line:84%
And this is also an opportunity
to learn something new

00:29:40.420 --> 00:29:43.480 align:middle line:84%
because it might appear
as if we are looking

00:29:43.480 --> 00:29:47.410 align:middle line:84%
over the shoulder of
a smarter classmate

00:29:47.410 --> 00:29:50.710 align:middle line:84%
to find answers to
fundamental questions,

00:29:50.710 --> 00:29:53.260 align:middle line:84%
like discovering
new technologies,

00:29:53.260 --> 00:29:55.990 align:middle line:84%
discovering new
science, new physics.

00:29:55.990 --> 00:30:00.580 align:middle line:84%
But if it saves us millions
of years, it's worth it.

00:30:00.580 --> 00:30:04.870 align:middle line:84%
And I would rather learn from
a smarter kid on our block

00:30:04.870 --> 00:30:10.280 align:middle line:84%
than try to invent
the will in a way.

00:30:10.280 --> 00:30:13.970 align:middle line:84%
So I think it's an opportunity
more than a risk for us.

00:30:13.970 --> 00:30:17.200 align:middle line:84%
>> So what's the most amazing or
the most exciting evidence that

00:30:17.200 --> 00:30:19.150 align:middle line:90%
you've collected so far?

00:30:19.150 --> 00:30:22.030 align:middle line:84%
>> That the first interstellar
meteor, for example,

00:30:22.030 --> 00:30:27.850 align:middle line:84%
discovered in 2014 was tougher
than all the other meteors

00:30:27.850 --> 00:30:29.860 align:middle line:84%
in the catalog that the
government compiled,

00:30:29.860 --> 00:30:32.320 align:middle line:90%
273 of them.

00:30:32.320 --> 00:30:37.425 align:middle line:84%
It was twice as tough as iron
because it disintegrated only

00:30:37.425 --> 00:30:38.800 align:middle line:84%
in the lower
atmosphere of Earth.

00:30:38.800 --> 00:30:41.090 align:middle line:84%
It was moving at 45
kilometers per second.

00:30:41.090 --> 00:30:42.190 align:middle line:90%
Very fast.

00:30:42.190 --> 00:30:44.830 align:middle line:84%
And that implied that it
had a very strong material

00:30:44.830 --> 00:30:46.330 align:middle line:84%
strength because
otherwise, it would

00:30:46.330 --> 00:30:48.500 align:middle line:90%
have disintegrated far above.

00:30:48.500 --> 00:30:51.700 align:middle line:84%
And the government
released the light curve

00:30:51.700 --> 00:30:53.380 align:middle line:84%
of the explosion
that took place.

00:30:53.380 --> 00:30:58.000 align:middle line:84%
And we analyzed it and realized
that it was tougher than iron.

00:30:58.000 --> 00:31:00.760 align:middle line:84%
And moreover, it
was moving faster

00:31:00.760 --> 00:31:03.880 align:middle line:84%
than 95% of all the stars
in the vicinity of the sun

00:31:03.880 --> 00:31:05.750 align:middle line:90%
outside the solar system.

00:31:05.750 --> 00:31:09.520 align:middle line:84%
And so maybe it
was a spacecraft.

00:31:09.520 --> 00:31:11.860 align:middle line:84%
The only way to find out
is to collect the fragments

00:31:11.860 --> 00:31:16.960 align:middle line:84%
from this explosion, which are
at the bottom of the Pacific

00:31:16.960 --> 00:31:20.020 align:middle line:84%
Ocean, about 100 miles off
the coast of Papua New Guinea.

00:31:20.020 --> 00:31:23.080 align:middle line:84%
>> So Avi, what evidence have
you captured with the Galileo

00:31:23.080 --> 00:31:24.040 align:middle line:90%
Project so far?

00:31:24.040 --> 00:31:26.207 align:middle line:84%
What's the most compelling
evidence you've captured?

00:31:26.207 --> 00:31:28.660 align:middle line:84%
>> Well, so far, we haven't
captured new data because we

00:31:28.660 --> 00:31:32.380 align:middle line:84%
just established the suite of
instruments that we are using.

00:31:32.380 --> 00:31:35.590 align:middle line:84%
And in coming months, we'll
test those instruments,

00:31:35.590 --> 00:31:39.950 align:middle line:84%
collect data, and analyze it
with artificial intelligence

00:31:39.950 --> 00:31:40.750 align:middle line:90%
algorithms.

00:31:40.750 --> 00:31:45.910 align:middle line:84%
And then we'll deploy those
instruments at a location

00:31:45.910 --> 00:31:48.760 align:middle line:84%
where unidentified
objects were reported.

00:31:48.760 --> 00:31:52.990 align:middle line:84%
And once we start collecting
data, we will analyze the data.

00:31:52.990 --> 00:31:55.630 align:middle line:84%
And eventually, hopefully,
within the coming year,

00:31:55.630 --> 00:31:57.790 align:middle line:90%
release it to the public.

00:31:57.790 --> 00:31:59.170 align:middle line:90%
>> What's the plan, Avi?

00:31:59.170 --> 00:32:03.010 align:middle line:84%
You have to have a plan in place
to present this to the media.

00:32:03.010 --> 00:32:06.160 align:middle line:84%
And what is that
Rubicon that you

00:32:06.160 --> 00:32:12.100 align:middle line:84%
have to cross of what is
presentable and exciting?

00:32:12.100 --> 00:32:13.670 align:middle line:90%
What's the plan?

00:32:13.670 --> 00:32:16.060 align:middle line:84%
>> First, we will make
sure that we understand how

00:32:16.060 --> 00:32:19.900 align:middle line:84%
the instruments work because
government data is collected

00:32:19.900 --> 00:32:23.290 align:middle line:84%
by instruments that they
have no full control over,

00:32:23.290 --> 00:32:26.570 align:middle line:84%
like if it's a camera in a
jittery cockpit of a fighter

00:32:26.570 --> 00:32:27.370 align:middle line:90%
jet.

00:32:27.370 --> 00:32:29.950 align:middle line:84%
You don't know exactly what
the fighter jet was doing.

00:32:29.950 --> 00:32:32.440 align:middle line:84%
We would have full control
over the instruments.

00:32:32.440 --> 00:32:35.950 align:middle line:84%
We will try to understand all
the systematic effects that

00:32:35.950 --> 00:32:37.310 align:middle line:90%
may come into play.

00:32:37.310 --> 00:32:40.960 align:middle line:90%
And then analyze the data.

00:32:40.960 --> 00:32:43.480 align:middle line:84%
Write a scientific
paper about it.

00:32:43.480 --> 00:32:45.520 align:middle line:84%
Submit it to a peer
reviewed journal.

00:32:45.520 --> 00:32:48.700 align:middle line:84%
And once it's accepted
for publication,

00:32:48.700 --> 00:32:52.330 align:middle line:84%
we'll release the data, make it
open, so anyone can analyze it.

00:32:52.330 --> 00:32:57.250 align:middle line:84%
So that's the scientific process
of getting peer reviewed data

00:32:57.250 --> 00:33:00.170 align:middle line:84%
to be open to the
scientific community.

00:33:00.170 --> 00:33:04.870 align:middle line:84%
And if we do find a
visitor in our backyard,

00:33:04.870 --> 00:33:08.680 align:middle line:84%
the implications
will be dramatic.

00:33:08.680 --> 00:33:11.590 align:middle line:84%
The search for extraterrestrial
intelligence in the past

00:33:11.590 --> 00:33:14.800 align:middle line:84%
was looking for radio
signals from stars that are

00:33:14.800 --> 00:33:16.690 align:middle line:90%
thousands of light years away.

00:33:16.690 --> 00:33:20.480 align:middle line:84%
And if we were to detect such
a signal, which by the way,

00:33:20.480 --> 00:33:23.710 align:middle line:84%
is a very naive
proposition because we

00:33:23.710 --> 00:33:26.860 align:middle line:84%
developed radio communication
only over the past century.

00:33:26.860 --> 00:33:29.440 align:middle line:84%
And we are backing
off from it right now

00:33:29.440 --> 00:33:33.010 align:middle line:84%
because we have fiber optic
for transferring data,

00:33:33.010 --> 00:33:34.960 align:middle line:90%
rather than radio.

00:33:34.960 --> 00:33:37.060 align:middle line:84%
We are also using
lasers for radio

00:33:37.060 --> 00:33:39.980 align:middle line:90%
for communication in space.

00:33:39.980 --> 00:33:44.770 align:middle line:84%
And so another civilization
using this primitive mode

00:33:44.770 --> 00:33:47.170 align:middle line:84%
of communication for
a long period of time

00:33:47.170 --> 00:33:50.410 align:middle line:90%
is not necessarily out there.

00:33:50.410 --> 00:33:53.920 align:middle line:84%
And moreover, civilizations
may have a lifetime

00:33:53.920 --> 00:33:56.170 align:middle line:84%
that could be quite
short once they

00:33:56.170 --> 00:33:57.610 align:middle line:84%
develop their
technologies because

00:33:57.610 --> 00:33:58.870 align:middle line:90%
of self-inflicted wounds.

00:33:58.870 --> 00:34:02.140 align:middle line:84%
So searching for those
signals make little sense

00:34:02.140 --> 00:34:03.760 align:middle line:84%
because those
signals may have been

00:34:03.760 --> 00:34:05.480 align:middle line:90%
generated a billion years ago.

00:34:05.480 --> 00:34:08.060 align:middle line:84%
And by now, they're a
billion light years away.

00:34:08.060 --> 00:34:14.590 align:middle line:84%
However, if those civilizations
sent anything to space, probes,

00:34:14.590 --> 00:34:18.070 align:middle line:84%
those probes are still
confined by gravity

00:34:18.070 --> 00:34:19.310 align:middle line:90%
to the Milky Way galaxy.

00:34:19.310 --> 00:34:23.080 align:middle line:84%
So they collect in this basket
called the Milky Way galaxy,

00:34:23.080 --> 00:34:25.550 align:middle line:90%
and we can find them around us.

00:34:25.550 --> 00:34:27.850 align:middle line:84%
And now the question
is what to do if we

00:34:27.850 --> 00:34:30.808 align:middle line:90%
find a visitor in our backyard?

00:34:30.808 --> 00:34:32.350 align:middle line:84%
It's a completely
different situation

00:34:32.350 --> 00:34:36.130 align:middle line:84%
because you don't have
the luxury of saying, OK,

00:34:36.130 --> 00:34:39.219 align:middle line:84%
the signal came from
1,000 light years away.

00:34:39.219 --> 00:34:40.810 align:middle line:90%
Therefore, it took 2,000 years.

00:34:40.810 --> 00:34:42.730 align:middle line:90%
We have 1,000 years to respond.

00:34:42.730 --> 00:34:44.020 align:middle line:90%
There's plenty of time.

00:34:44.020 --> 00:34:45.130 align:middle line:90%
No rush.

00:34:45.130 --> 00:34:49.770 align:middle line:84%
Here, it's like having a
person in your backyard,

00:34:49.770 --> 00:34:51.370 align:middle line:84%
you have to do
something about it.

00:34:51.370 --> 00:34:52.770 align:middle line:90%
We don't have a protocol.

00:34:52.770 --> 00:34:55.120 align:middle line:90%
And who represents humanity?

00:34:55.120 --> 00:34:57.810 align:middle line:84%
We don't have an
organization that does it.

00:34:57.810 --> 00:34:59.640 align:middle line:84%
What to do about the
technological gap?

00:34:59.640 --> 00:35:02.040 align:middle line:84%
Suppose this device
is very advanced

00:35:02.040 --> 00:35:06.810 align:middle line:84%
relative to what we possess,
how do we interpret its intent?

00:35:06.810 --> 00:35:11.220 align:middle line:84%
Imagine ants on a
sidewalk witnessing

00:35:11.220 --> 00:35:13.660 align:middle line:84%
a biker that stopped
just next to them

00:35:13.660 --> 00:35:16.530 align:middle line:84%
and starting to discuss what
protocol should we follow

00:35:16.530 --> 00:35:18.390 align:middle line:90%
in engaging with this biker?

00:35:18.390 --> 00:35:19.920 align:middle line:90%
That's completely irrelevant.

00:35:19.920 --> 00:35:22.620 align:middle line:84%
The biker wouldn't care
less about these ants.

00:35:22.620 --> 00:35:24.670 align:middle line:90%
The biker may step on them.

00:35:24.670 --> 00:35:28.360 align:middle line:84%
And so whatever we do might
not be really relevant.

00:35:28.360 --> 00:35:31.170 align:middle line:84%
What we should do at
first is figure out

00:35:31.170 --> 00:35:34.440 align:middle line:84%
what the intent of
any device we find is

00:35:34.440 --> 00:35:37.230 align:middle line:84%
and what the property,
the physical properties

00:35:37.230 --> 00:35:38.430 align:middle line:90%
of this device is.

00:35:38.430 --> 00:35:40.380 align:middle line:84%
Does it represent
technologies that

00:35:40.380 --> 00:35:43.200 align:middle line:84%
are way beyond what
we can imagine,

00:35:43.200 --> 00:35:46.920 align:middle line:84%
just like a cell phone
represents technologies

00:35:46.920 --> 00:35:49.140 align:middle line:84%
that a cave dweller
would never imagine?

00:35:49.140 --> 00:35:52.770 align:middle line:84%
Imagine a cave dweller
going to New York City,

00:35:52.770 --> 00:35:54.600 align:middle line:84%
seeing all the
gadgets out there.

00:35:54.600 --> 00:35:56.252 align:middle line:90%
That would look like magic.

00:35:56.252 --> 00:35:57.210 align:middle line:90%
